 but also offering new perspectives on many of our current feelings and ideas about animals.Here, Porphyry makes a compelling argument for vegetarianism and asserts that the just treatment of animals makes us better people; Pliny the Elder praises the virtuosity of songbirds and the virtuousness of elephants; Plutarch has one of Circe’s pigs from the Odyssey make a serio-comic case for the dignity of the beasts of the field; Aristotle puts the study of animals on par with anthropology; we read timeless Aesopian fables, including “The Hen That Laid the Golden Egg” and “The Fox and the Grapes”; and there is much, much more.A Noah’s Ark of a book, How to Care about Animals is guaranteed to charm and inspire anyone who loves animals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAnimalsvLiterary collections. 0aClassical literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aClassical literature. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  a9780691240435 How to Care about Animals.  aAesop.  aAncient Roman.  aAncient Wisdom Series.  aAncient Wisdom.  aAnimal love.  aGreeks.  aM. D. Usher, Princeton University Press.  aM.D. Usher.  aOvid, classicist.  aPETA.  aPorphyry and Friends.  aRomans.  aUmwelt.  aanceint Rome.  aancient Greece.  aancient Greek.  aancient philosophers.  aancient philosophy.  aanimal activists.  aanimal health.  aanimals.  abears.  abiology.  abirds.  abooks for animal lovers.  acaring for animals.  aclassical literature.  aclassical studies.  acreatures.  acruelty.  adogs.  adomesticated.  aethics.  afable.  afarmer.  afarming.  ainterspecies.  alions'.  aloving animals.  aoctopuses.  aphilosophers.  aphilosophy.  arelationship with animals.  asnails.  avegetarian.  awild.  awolves.  azoology.1 aUsher, M. D.,